  "prompt": "Politicians and financial experts have often labelled China as a currency manipulator. If that is the case, then what should the Renminbi be worth?",
  "response": "The debate about China's currency valuation is complex, but economists generally argue that the Renminbi (RMB) is undervalued. Most estimates suggest the RMB should be 10-25% higher against the US dollar than its current market rate. \n\nKey factors influencing this assessment include:\n1. Purchasing Power Parity (PPP) comparisons\n2. China's trade surplus\n3. Productivity and economic growth rates\n4. Long-term currency valuation models\n\nHowever, precise valuation is challenging due to:\n- China's managed exchange rate system\n- Capital controls\n- Government intervention in currency markets\n\nThe US Treasury and some economists argue that China has historically kept the RMB artificially low to make its exports cheaper and maintain trade advantages. While China has allowed more flexibility in recent years, debates about fair valuation continue.\n\nUltimately, there's no single definitive \"correct\" value, but most analyses suggest the RMB is undervalued relative to market-driven exchange rates.",
